WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:05.000
Nick Crane, Software Engineer at Voltron Data

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:10.000
Hello, my name is Nick Crane, I'm a software engineer at Voltron Data

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:13.000
and I'm also one of the maintainers on the Apache Arrow project.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.000
I work mainly on the R package.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:19.000
I started learning R about 12 years ago

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:23.000
and I just got so excited about the idea of open source.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.000
I went from being this passive consumer of software

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
to now having this thing that I could pull apart.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.000
It was like seeing the Matrix, seeing inside all these functions and things like that.

00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:36.000
But despite that being quite a while ago,

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
it took me about six more years, I'd say,

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.000
to really start to connect with the R communities

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:43.000
and another few years on top of that to make my first contribution.

00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:47.000
So what I want to talk to you about today is the things that got in my way

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:50.000
and stopped me getting involved with contributing to open source a bit sooner

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:52.000
when I probably actually could have

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.000
and actually it's been so beneficial to me,

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:57.000
I almost wish I had sooner.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.000
But first, so in the way that everybody does science,

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.000
I wanted to do a Twitter poll.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:06.000
So question for my RStats folks who have contributed to open source,

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.000
how many years had you been using open source libraries for

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.000
before you made your first contribution?

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:13.000
And actually it was pretty interesting to see

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:17.000
that it was pretty nice to see that for most people pretty soon actually,

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:19.000
two to three years of using open source libraries

00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:21.000
before they kind of really got involved.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:23.000
But actually, you know, it's quite a lot of people

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:25.000
in a similar situation to I was

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:31.000
where six more years before they really kind of made that first leap.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:33.000
So I'm going to start off just by talking about

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:35.000
kind of why I contribute to open source

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:37.000
and the benefits it's had for me.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:40.000
But before I go into that, I just want to start with a bit of disclaimer.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:42.000
I'm not saying that contributing to open source

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.000
is necessary to be a good software engineer or a good data scientist.

00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:46.000
It's absolutely not.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.000
I think there's a certain amount of privilege

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.000
being involved with even having the time to do so alongside everything else.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:54.000
So that's not what I'm going for here.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:56.000
But going back to kind of like what I've gotten out

00:01:56.000 --> 00:01:58.000
of contributing to open source,

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:02.000
I feel like it's been the best learning experience of my career.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:05.000
Definitely kind of, you know, contributing kind of code

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
and non-code things and getting feedback from people

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:11.000
has been the biggest acceleration of my development as a software engineer.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:13.000
Working in public is great.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:15.000
You know, I figure out something that's taken me ages

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:17.000
and I blog about it and then somebody's like,

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:20.000
okay, I get it now, really rewarding.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
And again, it's great to be part of a community.

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:26.000
I think as well, it's great to have that proof of your skills.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Like, I'm not the most necessarily confident person as a software engineer,

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:31.000
but having those sort of bragging rights, you know,

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.000
like I've kind of made those contributions to that project,

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:37.000
okay, well, I guess I must know what I'm doing some of the time then.

00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:41.000
And also just like giving back to projects that have helped me in my work before.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:44.000
Okay, so that's kind of the benefits.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:46.000
But what are the kind of things that have kind of maybe got in my way

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:48.000
or some quite common complaints?

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.000
So like, I think one of the flip sides of open source

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.000
being this kind of massive network of self-governing communities

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.000
is that it has been quite kind of okay in some bits

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
to, you know, have kind of quite strong personalities

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
and people kind of not behaving amazingly in some bits anyway.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.000
So I think I definitely have that question, you know,

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:10.000
are people going to be friendly or mean?

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:12.000
There's also the question of not knowing how.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
So I was at a point where I could write functions

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:16.000
and even write R packages,

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:19.000
but I've not made a pull request for a project yet.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:21.000
Other questions are things like,

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:23.000
what if I don't have the skills to do this?

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.000
What if I don't know where to start?

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:27.000
And even just that fear that like working in public is scary.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.000
I get to share my successes,

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:33.000
but I also kind of share my failures a bit.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
So just to get kind of one barrier out of the way,

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
if it's literally just the process of how do I make a pull request

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.000
to a project that is stopping me from contributing to open source,

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.000
I'd say please do check out the first contributions repo

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:48.000
that's kind of looked after by forwards.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:51.000
So I was involved in kind of making the R version of this.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:53.000
And basically it takes you through the process

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:55.000
of making a pull request.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:58.000
So if you already know a bit of Git and know how to use GitHub,

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:00.000
that is all you need to kind of just walk through

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.000
the kind of mechanical steps for it.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:05.000
But actually I think the things that really hold people back

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:08.000
from getting involved aren't kind of the actual process things,

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:10.000
and it's more these kind of concerns or worries.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:13.000
So like the main bulk of this talk is going to be basically

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:17.000
about things that I now know that I wish I'd known before.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.000
Okay, so the first big question I had is how to pick where to get involved

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.000
and what to work on.

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:24.000
And I think this is just really complicated

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.000
by maybe the view that I had of open source.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:29.000
And I really had this kind of slightly misguided view at first

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:31.000
that open source is one big community.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
And that's just not true.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.000
There are lots of open source sub-communities.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:39.000
And even within languages, within R, we see this, right?

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:41.000
But I think even kind of stepping back from that,

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:44.000
kind of my next view of open source wasn't quite right either.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:46.000
So to kind of illustrate it,

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:48.000
so this is a screenshot from the movie Mean Girls.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:50.000
Now, if you've not seen that,

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.000
I'm sure everybody at some point has seen some TV show or movie

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:56.000
where you've got this kind of like American high school cafeteria

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
and the new kids walking through,

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:01.000
and it's like, are these people going to let me sit at their table or are they not?

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:04.000
And that feeling of, you know, these people are kind of mean

00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:06.000
and these people are kind of nice and things like that.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:10.000
And this metaphor completely breaks down because everybody's nerds here.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:13.000
But the point was like kind of viewing it as these people are mean

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:17.000
and awful and these people are lovely over here isn't quite right.

00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:20.000
I think with a lot of projects, it's easy to forget,

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:23.000
like a lot of projects are kind of staffed by volunteers.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.000
There's a lot of reasons why kind of some projects

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:27.000
just don't want new contributors.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.000
So they might be going through a design phase.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:31.000
They might just be really small.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:33.000
And it does take effort to onboard a new contributor.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:37.000
So I kind of came to realize that is okay.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:39.000
But then, of course, like the next obvious question is,

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:42.000
so if some projects don't want new contributors,

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:45.000
then how do I find the ones that do?

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.000
And actually that was way easier to answer than I thought.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.000
So they'll tell you.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.000
So, for example, this is an issue from the Arrow project.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.000
This is one that we've labeled good first issue to say, you know,

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:00.000
this is a good place to get started, get involved.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:02.000
And again, similarly, here's, I think this is an old one,

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.000
but this is from dplyr.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:06.000
And it's been labeled both good first issue and help wanted,

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:10.000
like clear signaling, like we want people to get involved here.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.000
I will say, like projects that don't have these labels,

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.000
it doesn't mean they don't want new contributors.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:16.000
But if this is a concern of yours,

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.000
this is kind of an easy way to kind of figure it out.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:23.000
So the next question I guess then that I had is what to contribute.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:26.000
And I think commonly given advice that I think is good advice

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:29.000
is all about starting small, build up trust, you know,

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:31.000
show people you've read the guidelines and you can kind of like

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:34.000
go from small things and bigger from there.

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:37.000
I think one thing that was really important for me, though, actually,

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:40.000
is it is way easier to contribute to packages

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:42.000
that you use yourself.

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
So my first contribution was to the broom package,

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.000
and that went well in everything, but there were points

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:49.000
during that kind of code contribution where I was like,

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:51.000
I don't know if I can change this because I wasn't a regular user

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.000
of the package.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
And it would have been much easier if it was something

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:57.000
that I had a bit more kind of day-to-day use with.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:00.000
And of course, like if you found problems in packages

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:02.000
or bugs that you've experienced yourself,

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:04.000
that's a really great place to get involved,

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
kind of figuring out what's going on, fixing it,

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:08.000
making a pull request.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.000
Equally with documentation you find unclear,

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.000
I feel like if you're newer to something,

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:14.000
you're actually an advantage here.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
Like you're coming to this problem with kind of like

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.000
a fresh mindset, and therefore like if the documentation

00:07:18.000 --> 00:07:20.000
doesn't make sense to you, it's probably not going to make sense

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.000
to somebody else, and that's a really nice early contribution

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.000
to make.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:28.000
And just in general, if you've got a specific maybe area

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:30.000
that you've got expertise, domain knowledge,

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:32.000
that's also a great place to go and kind of like use that

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.000
if there's a package that deals with that.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:36.000
Okay.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
So I think for me the really, really, really big question

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.000
about how to get involved was how to navigate social dynamics.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:46.000
And this is a really tricky one, because as I said before,

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:50.000
every project is different and made up of quite different people

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:52.000
even kind of within the same project.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.000
Now there's this quote that I really like actually.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
So there's this book called Working in Public

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:59.000
by Nadia Agbal, and if you're interested in kind of

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
open source governance and how these things work,

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:02.000
I would definitely recommend it.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.000
Really good book.

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:05.000
In the book, Nadia says,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:08.000
open source is complicated because it contains a messy mix

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:10.000
of both technical and social norms,

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:12.000
most of which play out in public.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.000
And I think this really gets to it for me.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:17.000
It's figuring out how to kind of change something,

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:19.000
make a function, and that's one thing.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:22.000
But just figuring out how to be this new person in this group

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:25.000
and kind of go in and not annoy people

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:27.000
and kind of just get things done,

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:30.000
that can be really tricky.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
So one of the ways of overcoming this, I think,

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:36.000
is a lot of projects have kind of contributing guidelines

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:37.000
and documentation.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:40.000
So this is kind of like a screenshot of a page

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
that I really, really like actually.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:44.000
It's the Apache Software Foundation

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:46.000
kind of member participation guidelines.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:49.000
And it goes into detail, even like the minute detail

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:52.000
of kind of like how to kind of phrase requests

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:54.000
to kind of make significant changes

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:58.000
to make it kind of as, I guess, as smoothly as possible.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:00.000
They say this doesn't just apply

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
to Apache Software Foundation projects.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:04.000
And it's definitely worth kind of skimming through these

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:07.000
if that's kind of a concern that you have yourself.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:09.000
But then the other thing here, I think,

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.000
is like sometimes just embracing imposter syndrome.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
Like you are new to this thing, and that's great.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
But like if you were pretending to be somebody

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:18.000
that was there already, what would you do?

00:09:18.000 --> 00:09:20.000
So the answer could be you can go and read

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
previous pull requests and previous issues

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
and look at the kind of things that people do.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
So like every different package

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
is going to have something slightly different.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:30.000
It's always good just to see what the conventions are

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
and to follow them.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
I will say the one thing to kind of add to that

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:36.000
is as a new contributor, it's sometimes better

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
to err on the side of over-communicating

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:40.000
rather than under-communicating.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:42.000
Because an established kind of contributor

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:44.000
might kind of need to say less to get something accepted.

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:47.000
But still, I found reading those previous PRs and issues

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:50.000
has been like super, super useful.

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:51.000
Okay.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:53.000
Now, this is a really weird one for me.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:55.000
Something I've noticed, and again,

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:57.000
this is very different between different projects,

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.000
but definitely on some,

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.000
there's this real difference in social norms

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:03.000
and quite stark differences

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.000
between what would come across a certain way in real life

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:09.000
versus kind of how things look in a pull request.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:11.000
So to step back a second,

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
we've got these projects that have maybe got busy maintainers,

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.000
lots of different issues,

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.000
and there's a certain level of bluntness

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:19.000
that can appear rude,

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
but it's people just trying to get through issues

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
and just trying to get as much done as possible.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
And I've definitely had to kind of come to terms

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
with this real duality

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.000
of kind of maybe seeing that kind of feedback

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.000
and getting it myself

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
and not taking it as rude or personal or anything like that

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
and just seeing it for what it is.

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
But at the same time, actually not necessarily engaging

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:39.000
in that communication style too much myself

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.000
because I don't like it.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
And just because it's a normal thing,

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
it doesn't mean I have to do it.

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
But again, I can still exist in that world,

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
and that is fine.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.000
So kind of my third question then

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.000
was what does the process of getting a pull request

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
actually look like?

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:57.000
And this is another one where I've really had to kind of change my,

00:10:57.000 --> 00:10:59.000
I guess, the way that I view these kind of things.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:01.000
So previously,

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.000
I kind of viewed it a bit like an essay.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
So you're in school, you do an essay,

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
you do your work, you check it,

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
you hand it in to somebody,

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
and then you wait a bit and you get it back,

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
and you've got some kind of mark that's an indication

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:15.000
of your skill or competence.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
That is really not a good way to look at a pull request.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
You will have a bad time if you do that.

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
And the reason for that is

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
a pull request is more like a conversation

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:25.000
than an essay.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
The back and forth and suggestions for changing things

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
and taking a different approach,

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.000
that is part of one of the best things

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.000
about getting involved in open source.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:35.000
That is when you are really learning.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:37.000
That is when you're getting feedback from people

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.000
that are probably quite experienced at this

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
to improve things.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
So yeah, definitely not treating it like an essay.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
And I think another thing kind of around

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:47.000
this kind of pull request kind of approach

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.000
as well is I've found

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:51.000
that coming from a background where I've been working

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.000
in kind of consultancy and a bit of software engineering

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
on proprietary projects,

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:57.000
working on open source libraries

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:59.000
is a completely different thing

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
in some really subtle ways.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.000
And this is something that I summarize

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
as a task-oriented versus code-oriented approach.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
So when I was a consultant,

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:09.000
I would be working

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
building things with libraries.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
So the focus there is getting tasks done.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:15.000
You might be building an app for a user

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.000
that needs to do a certain thing as part of their day job.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
You might have a known set of users

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:22.000
or at least some of them you could maybe go

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
sit down with them and see how they'd normally do that task.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:26.000
And it makes it a bit easier really

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
to kind of see what they're likely to do

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:30.000
and what they're not likely to do.

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:32.000
And you can kind of get away with only testing

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
kind of like certain paths.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
In these circumstances,

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
dependencies can be a lot less important.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
You can add in new packages and it not be a big deal.

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
And you might be the only maintainer

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
or part of a small team.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:46.000
So you can kind of do things however you want

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
as long as it works.

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
But this is completely different now

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
working in open source libraries.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:54.000
Your users and your tasks are mostly unknown

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:56.000
which means you have to be really rigorous

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:58.000
with your testing and even kind of preventing

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:00.000
paths that you think no one will ever take

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:02.000
or testing things that you think no one will ever use

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
actually does become quite important.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:06.000
There's often kind of a need

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
to really avoid adding extra dependencies here.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
But that can lead to really good things.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:12.000
So I think sometimes

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:14.000
it can be easy to say, right,

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:16.000
let's just use this other one or a bit from both.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:18.000
But when you're working on kind of open source libraries,

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:20.000
you kind of can't do that.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:22.000
But that forces you then

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:24.000
to learn to work with the tools that you've got in front of you

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
and learn that kind of last 10%

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:28.000
of a library to get tasks done.

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:30.000
And I think, again, that's been something

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:32.000
that's been really valuable for me.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:34.000
And also just this idea that you're writing code

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
that isn't kind of your code.

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.000
This is to be maintained by kind of maybe yourself

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
but other people in the community.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:42.000
And that means you can't have

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:44.000
these maybe weird idiosyncrasies

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.000
or kind of code smells.

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
You've got to be a bit more strict

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.000
about these kind of things.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:52.000
And I think just kind of realizing

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
that it's a really different kind of mindset

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:56.000
between these two things

00:13:56.000 --> 00:13:58.000
kind of makes it a bit easier to accept

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
what kind of might seem like pedantry sometimes

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
but it's actually for a really good purpose.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
But actually,

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
this isn't even the right question.

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:08.000
You could submit a pull request

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.000
to a project

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
and it might not get accepted.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
And that could be a good thing.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
You could try to implement something

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:18.000
that doesn't quite work

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
but it exposes something else in the package

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:22.000
that actually needs changing and updating.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:24.000
And that's a helpful contribution.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
You've figured something out

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:28.000
that can make the software better.

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:30.000
And actually, I think the question should be

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
how do I make a meaningful contribution?

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:34.000
Because actually, when I think about it,

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
I feel really good about the code

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
that I've kind of contributed towards

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.000
because I think some of my most meaningful

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:42.000
open source contributions have nothing to do with code.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
I love writing blog posts

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
when I've learned something that I found difficult

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:48.000
and then somebody else is like,

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:50.000
yeah, no, that makes sense to me now, finally.

00:14:50.000 --> 00:14:52.000
I love improving documentation

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:54.000
and taking that kind of beginner's mindset.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:14:56.000
Even tweeting about a bit of functionality

00:14:56.000 --> 00:14:58.000
that is not well advertised

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
and somebody's suddenly like,

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
I can now achieve something with that.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:04.000
I feel like that's kind of meaningful.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
So to summarize then,

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.000
it's about people.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:10.000
There isn't a single open source community.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
There's a lot of different sub-communities within things.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
And there's no one-size-fits-all approach

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
to saying you should do this here

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:18.000
or you should behave like that in that way.

00:15:18.000 --> 00:15:20.000
It's about kind of just figuring it out

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:22.000
for the thing that you're actually looking at at the time.

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.000
I think,

00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:26.000
especially maybe as a new and more nervous person,

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
just find communities that you want to be part of

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
and want you to be part of them.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
Also, just remember

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
everybody is new at some point

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:36.000
and once you have done the work of reading the guidelines

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.000
and kind of a few previous pull requests

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:40.000
and approaches,

00:15:40.000 --> 00:15:42.000
after that there's a point at which you just have to jump right in

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:44.000
and go for it and then welcome

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:46.000
that kind of code review conversation.

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
But as much as I'm talking about code now,

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.000
open source contributions

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:52.000
are about way more than just code

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
and that is definitely something to keep in mind.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:56.000
Okay, thank you.

00:15:56.000 --> 00:15:58.000
Applause

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
Music

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
